        "unit": "mm/s",
        "description": "Effective for light contamination (e.g., oxides) at higher speeds; slower (500-1000 mm/s) for heavy buildup. Recommended 1500 mm/s optimizes cleaning rate while minimizing heat input on Zr's melting point (1855°C). Source: Industry manuals (e.g., CleanLaser systems) and process optimization in Nucl. Eng. Des. 2020."
      },
      "pulse_width": {
        "min": 0.1,
        "max": 1000,
        "unit": "ns",
        "value": 20,
        "description": "Nanosecond regime preferred for industrial cleaning of Zr to ablate contaminants with minimal HAZ; picosecond (5-50 ps) for ultra-low thermal effects but costlier. 20 ns recommended to limit plasma shielding on reflective surfaces. Source: Laser physics reviews (Opt. Lasers Eng. 2019) and ablation studies on Zr alloys."
      },
      "repetition_rate": {
        "min": 1,
        "max": 200,
        "value": 30,
        "unit": "kHz",
        "description": "Typical for 1064 nm cleaning; higher rates (>50 kHz) speed up process but risk heat accumulation on low-conductivity Zr. 30 kHz balances throughput and safety. Trade-off: faster cleaning vs. potential subsurface heating. Source: Academic literature on pulsed laser cleaning (Appl. Surf. Sci. 2021)."
      },
